04222nam a22006615i 9780824841621DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221989hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248416217 a10.1515/97808248416212doi  a(DE-B1597)613471  a(OCoLC)1322126212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aP211b.D36 1989eb 7aLAN0050002bisacsh04a4112191 aDeFrancis, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aVisible Speech :bThe Diverse Oneness of Writing Systems /cJohn DeFrancis. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©1989  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tI WRITING IN COMMUNICATIVE CONTEXT -- t1. Kinds of Communication -- t2. What Is Writing? -- tII FULL WRITING SYSTEMS -- t3. Syllabic Systems -- t4. Consonantal Systems -- t5. Alphabetic Systems -- tIII WRITING IN COMPARATIVE PERSPECTIVE -- t6. A Critique of Writing about Writing -- t7. The Essential Oneness of Full Writing -- tNOTES -- tGLOSSARY -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVisible Speech is an attempt to set the record straight about the nature of writing. John DeFrancis, a noted specialist in the Chinese language, shows that writing can be based only upon a sound system and not upon any other linguistic level. He corrects the erroneous views of Chinese writing as pictographic, ideographic, logographic, or morphemic, and defends his conclusion that because of these misrepresentations, the nature of all writing continues to be misunderstood. Using the writing systems of Sumerian, Egyptian, Arabic, Japanese, Korean, Greek, Mayan, and English, among others, to illustrate his points, Dr. DeFrancis stresses their basic identity as representatives of visible speech, while noting their secondary differences as manifested in their diverse script forms. He proposes a new classification of writing systems based on this theme of diversity and oneness, and makes an impassioned case for the essential phonetic component of all writing. This book reflects the author's sound scholarship and novel insights, which place it in the forefront with such classics on writing as those by Gelb, Diringer, Cohen, Février, and Jensen. The readable style aims at a general audience interested in understanding the nature of the symbols that first strike the eye, while the academic research involved makes it an indispensable work for scholars in the many fields related to language and linguistics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aWriting. 0aWritten communication. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484162140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824841621423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824841621/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK